troduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Danbie I was born in 1330, in Danby, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 son with Lady Agnes de Grene. He died in Farnley, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1330–":"1330–Surnud","1341–1391":"1341–1391","1350–Male":"1350–Surnud","1330–Male":"1330–Surnud","1330":"1330","1341":"1341","1350":"1350","1391":"1391","about 1350":"umbes 1350","Farnley Hall, Yorkshire, England":"Farnley, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Danby Wisk, North Riding, Yorkshire, England":"Danby, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Danby, Yorkshire, England":"Danby, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"1330–":"1330–Kuollut","1341–1391":"1341–1391","1350–Male":"1350–Kuollut","1330–Male":"1330–Kuollut","1330":"1330","1341":"1341","1350":"1350","1391":"1391","about 1350":"noin 1350","Farnley Hall, Yorkshire, England":"Farnley, Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Danby Wisk, North Riding, Yorkshire, England":"Danby, Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Danby, Yorkshire, England":"Danby, Yorkshire, England"},"fr":{"1330–":"1330–Décédé","1341–1391":"1341–1391","1350–Male":"1350–Décédé","1330–Male":"1330–Décédé","1330":"1330","1341":"1341","135